the idea with the blacklist is that any model-serving peer is only incentivized to respond to a peer (e.g. a Validator) that has enough stake that said peers' ranking will impact dividends positively
so if you don't have a lot of stake, why waste my compute, and potentially have to serve you over a higher staked peer
Right. But if users are all -randomly arbitrarily- setting this value, there's no cohesion, no?
the cohesion doesn't matter much here
because it's only servers with the blacklist
if most of the servers set it too high then there's a market for a peer with a lower blacklist as they would capture most of the dividends from these blacklisted peers
a lot of it is to reduce spam requests
you're unlikely to get spam requests from higher stake peers
also, there's still some incentive to not blacklist as it decreases consensus
and even then, you'll want to respond to them because how do you know what response they'll rank you on

We used to give a more in depth description. We had a whole page for it actually, but ultimately the docs are not here to explain the more technical workings of the network

**The 1024t stake to be a validator, is a myth**
>> You can stake with anything. But it's proportionate to your stake amount if you're a "good enough peer".  Too low and it wont matter and it's a waste. 1024t is ```stakePruningMin ```, which prevents you to de-register when you have no work, but hold more than that value.

**Miner's can blacklist, but why use this option?**
>> ```--neuron.blacklist.stake.forward <>``` Quoting vune: "The idea with the blacklist is that any model-serving peer is only incentivized to respond to a peer (e.g. a Validator) that has enough stake that said peers' ranking will impact dividends positively" Set it too low, and you burn yourself, vice versa applies.

I will add to this announcement: https://canary.discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/830075335084474390/1045033438484365392

**First off:** i'm not pointing fingers to anybody, this key being deployed as is, on my side, _was_ bad deployment.
It came to my attention a coldkey was compromised and siphoning staked - and in wallet - Tao. Some investigation is still happening, but it's safe to say, be **careful how you use your keys.** How they got access to the wallet, is still unknown, all we know is that they have been able to regenerate the coldkey.
 
Tl-dr: if you dont need to stake/unstake on a specific machine (i.e mining for keys), just deploy with --ss58 <coldkey>; currently i have **a** coldkey compromised. Because you can't move miners to a new coldkey, that means anything attached to that coldkey is stuck.
